  "raw_html": "<button type='button' role='link' class='btn btn-link p-0 text-start' id='link_3' aria-label=\" Thirunagalingam versus Lingeswaran & Anr. pdf\"  class='noToken' href='#' onclick=javascript:open_pdf('3','2025','2025_6_253_265','2025INSC672'); ><font size='4'> <strong>THIRUNAGALINGAM<span class='fst-italic'> versus </span>LINGESWARAN & ANR. </strong>- <span class='escrText'>[2025] 6 S.C.R. 253</span><span class='ncDisplay'>2025 INSC 672</span><input type='hidden' id='cnr' value=ESCR010001912025></button></font><br><strong>Coram : B.V. NAGARATHNA<sup style=\"color: #268e97;font-size: 22px;top: 0;\" class=\"tooltip-sup\" data-tooltip=\"Author\">*</sup>, SATISH CHANDRA SHARMA</strong><br> Issue for Consideration An appeal suit along with the application for condonation of delay of 1116 days was preferred. The High Court allowed the application for condonation of delay of 1116 days. Whether the delay is to be condoned or not, and if the delay is justifiable, then whether the case or be dismissed on procedural grounds. Headnotes&dagger; Code of Civil Procedure, 1908 &ndash; Or. XLI, r.3A and s.151 &ndash; In the first round of litigation, respondents could not succeed in setting aside the ex-parte decree passed by the Trial Court in the suit, and hence they preferred<br><strong class='caseDetailsTD' ><span style='color:#212F3D' > Decision Date :</span><font color='green'> 12-05-2025</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Case No :</span><font color='green'> CIVIL APPEAL No. 6843/2025</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Disposal Nature :</span><font color='green'> Appeal(s) allowed</font>   <span style='color:#212F3D' > |  Bench :</span><font color='green'> 2 Judges</font></strong><div class='row my-1 mt-2 border bg-light'><div class='col-auto'><a href='#' class='btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm my-1' onclick=open_splitview('3','2025','2025_6_253_265','2025INSC672','S')><i <i class='fas fa-columns me-2'></i>Split view</a></div><div class='col-auto'><a href='